:"1250–Deceased","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>pope</i> (derived via Old English from Late Latin <i>papa</i> ‘bishop, pope’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’, in origin a nursery word.) In the early Christian Church, the Latin term was at first used as a title of respect for male clergy of every rank, but in the Western Church it gradually came to be restricted to bishops, and then only to the bishop of Rome; in the Eastern Church it continued to be used of all priests (see   Popov  ,   Papas  ). The nickname would have been used for a vain or pompous man, or for someone who had played the part of the pope in a pageant or play. The surname is also present in Ireland and Scotland.","North German: variant of   Poppe  .","German: translation of   Pabst  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Popov","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Nikolay, Oleg, Grigoriy, Anatoly, Andrei, Arkadi, Dmitriy, Mikhail, Sergey.  Bulgarian or Macedonian Atanas, Dimitar, Yordan.  Serbian Bosko, Bozidar, Branko.","Russian, Bulgarian, Macedonian, Serbian, and Rusyn: patronymic from <i>pop</i> ‘priest’, from Greek <i>pappas</i> ‘father’ (compare English   Pope  ). The name may sometimes derive from a nickname, but celibacy was not enjoined on priests of the Orthodox Church and so the name can indeed mean ‘son of the priest’. In many cases, however, the Russian name means no more than ‘of the priest’ and designates a servant of a priest. Compare   Popoff  , see also   Pop   2,   Popovic  , and   Popovski   1.","Jewish (American): most likely a shortened form of   Popovski   2. Compare   Popoff  ."]},{"name":"Papke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Bernhard, Erwin, Hans, Otto, Willi.","North German (also <b>Päpke</b>): nickname from a diminutive of Low German <i>pape</i>, Dutch <i>paepe</i> ‘pope’. Compare   Pope  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Pope was born in 1250, in England. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1250–":"1250–Surnud","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"1250–":"1250–Kuollut","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1250–Mal